                        Buy or subscribe

Laura Bakkensen of the University of Oregon, USA, and Lint Barrage of ETH Zurich, Switzerland, developed a joint empirical–structural approach to overcome the “micro–macro” gap. They first review the existing literature through a harmonized sample and discuss how the existing divergence can be resolved. Then they estimate cyclone impacts on structural determinants of growth to quantify a specific cyclone–climate–economy model for 40 vulnerable nations. They confirm that future cyclone risks can impose massive welfare costs on many poor and small island countries. Interestingly, the USA is also among the top impacted countries despite its high income and constant exposure. Furthermore, the model also considers behavioural adjustments, and the long-run impacts of growing storm risks can be smaller than the previously estimated short-run impacts.Original reference: Econ. J. https://doi.org/10.1093/ej/ueaf050 (2025)



